{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is wiring across CSV parsing, schema validation, and DLQ publishing. A unit test of only the validator can miss row-number propagation bugs or incorrect DLQ payload mapping.","test_description":"Run the row-processing pipeline on a small CSV fixture containing valid and invalid rows. Use the real parser, schema validator, and DLQ writer implementation (backed by local test storage). Assert that invalid rows are excluded from normalized output and that each DLQ record contains the exact original CSV row number and raw row payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic transformation logic in one boundary (date parsing/normalization). No I/O or external infrastructure is required to catch real parsing/canonicalization failures.","test_description":"Table-driven unit test for the date-normalization function with representative ISO 8601, US (MM/DD/YYYY), and European (DD/MM/YYYY) inputs, including ambiguous and invalid cases. Assert exact canonical output (or rejection) for each input.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on runtime memory behavior, throughput, and timeout enforcement under realistic load. In-process mocks can hide buffering or backpressure issues that only appear with real process/resource limits.","test_description":"Execute the pipeline as a real process against a generated 500,000-row CSV and real local sinks (e.g., Postgres test instance and DLQ target). Enforce the production-like timeout, capture peak RSS memory, and assert completion before timeout and below memory budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.87,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real HTTP error handling/retry behavior across the S3 client stack and timing/backoff logic. Pure mocks can mask SDK-level behavior differences and retry misconfiguration.","test_description":"Run pipeline against an S3-compatible test endpoint (or HTTP fault-injection proxy) that returns 503 for initial GET attempts, then succeeds. Verify batch eventually succeeds and observed retry delays follow configured exponential backoff bounds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This crosses persistence semantics plus crash/restart behavior. A lower-level test can miss duplicate insertion caused by real restart timing, transaction boundaries, or checkpoint recovery in the running process.","test_description":"Start a real pipeline run writing to a real Postgres test database, force termination mid-batch, then restart from recovery/checkpoint state. Assert final row count equals unique input rows and no duplicate keys/records exist